1 Correlation

1.0.1 Correlation vs Regression

  • Major difference between correlation and regression is the purpose. Correlation tries to define relationship, regression is done for predictiong a value.

  • Correlation does not imply causation.

  • Correlation measures the relationship between two variables.

  • Regression analysis is about how one variable affects another or what changes it causes to the other.

  • Correlation captures the degree of interrelation between two variables.

  • Regression is based on causality. It shows no degree of connection but cause and effect.

  • In correlation ; p(X,Y)=p(Y,X), correlation is symmetrical.

  • Regression is one way analysis.

  • Linear regression analysis is known for the best fitting line that goes through the data points and minimizes the distance between them.

  • Correlation is a single point.

  • Regression line : the best fitting line through the data points

  • The slope of the regression line is beta1.

  • The intercept of the regression line with the y axis is beta0 and it is a constant.

  • The distance between observed values and the regression line is the estimator of the error, epsilon.

  • The estimate is called residual.

  • Each time we create a regression that should be meaningful!

  • Linear Regression : A linear approximation of a causal relationship between two or more variables. They are highly valuable as they are one of the most common ways to make inferences and predictions.

  • Correlation is scale independent.

  • Regression analysis is scale dependent.

  • Slope of the regression line has the same sign as the correlation coefficient.

  • If the correlation is zero, the regression line is horizontal with a slope of zero.

  • An important consequence of scale independence in correlation is that the correlation between X and y is the same as the correlation between y^ and y. They are equal because the regression equation itself. y^ is a simple rescaling of X variable. (y^=a+bX)

1.0.2 Assumptions in Correlation

  • Sample was randomly selected and the two variables, X and Y, vary together in a joint distribution that is normally distributed, called the bivariate normal distribution. Just because each variable is normally distributed when examined separately, however, does not guarantee that, jointly, they have a bivariate normal distribution.
  • If either of the two variables is not normally distributed, Pearson’s product moment correlation coefficient is not the most appropriate method. - - Instead, either one or both of the variables may be transformed so that they more closely follow a normal distribution.
  • Or Spearman rank correlation may be calculated.

1.0.3 Calculating Correlation

  • Calculating correlation
  • Presenting problem: Neidert and colleagues (2016) studied the relationship between body composition measurements: plasma DPP-IV activity, gynoid fat, BM and lean mass. They recruited 111 subjects from Auburn University (40 men and 77 women) and collected the body composition variables for the study.

1.0.3.1 The t test for Correlation

  • The symbol for the correlation coefficient in the population (the population parameter) is p (lowercase Greek letter rho). In a random sample, p estimated by r.
  • If several random samples of the same size are selected from a given population and the correlation coefficient r is calculated for each, we expect r to vary from one sample to another but to follow some sort of distribution about the population value p.

# Calculation
# H0: No relationship exists between BMI and percent body fat.
# Or, the true correlation is zero: p = 0.
# H1: A relationship does exist between BMI and percent body fat.
# Or, the true correlation is not zero: p ≠ 0.

cor.test(x=Fat_data$BMI, y=Fat_data$Percent.Fat,
    method="pearson",
    alternative = "two.sided",
    conf.level = 0.95)
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  Fat_data$BMI and Fat_data$Percent.Fat
## t = 4.8471, df = 109, p-value = 4.181e-06
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.2546933 0.5632773
## sample estimates:
##       cor 
## 0.4210956
# The null hypothesis of zero correlation is therefore rejected.
# And we conclude that:
# The relationship between BMI and percent body fat is large enough 
# to conclude that these two variables are associated.

# Creating publication ready graphics
library(ggpubr)
ggscatter(Fat_data, x = "BMI",y = "Percent.Fat", 
          add = "reg.line", conf.int = TRUE, 
          cor.coef = TRUE, cor.method = "pearson",
          xlab = "BMI kg/m2", ylab = "% Fat",
          color = "black",conf.int.level = 0.95,
          ellipse=FALSE)

# The correlation between BMI and percent body fat is 0.42
# Indicating a strong relationship between these two measures.


- The size of the correlation required for statistical significance is related to the sample size. With a very large sample of subjects, such as 2000, even small correlations, such as 0.06, are significant. - The coefficient of determination tells us how strong the relationship really is. In the health literature, confidence limits or results of a statistical test for significance of the correlation coefficient are also commonly presented.

1.0.3.2 Fisher’s z Transformation to Test The Correlation

  • It is used when we want to check whether the correlation is equal to specific value other then zero.
  • It is performed to show that the correlation is greater than a given value, or a confidence interval about the observed correlation can be calculated In either case, we use a procedure called Fisher’s z transformation to test any null hypothesis about the correlation as well as to form confidence intervals.
  • To use Fisher’s exact test, we first transform the correlation and then use the standard normal (z) distribution. We need to transform the correlation because, the distribution of sample values of the correlation is skewed when p≠0.
  • Actually we don’t really need to do this transformation because cor.test function can return conf intervals for correlation values. For example: For %95 confidence correlation in our example is greater than 0.25.

1.1 Comparing Two Correlation Coefficients

1.1.1 Comparing Correlations In Two Independent Groups

  • Fisher’s z transformation can be used to test hypotheses or form confidence intervals about the difference between the correlations between the same two variables in two independent groups. The results of such tests are also called independent correlations.

### Comparing Correlations In Two Independent Groups ***

  • When the research question involves correlations that contain the same variable (also called dependent correlations).
  • Pereira and colleagues (2015) was whether one of the bedside glucose devices was more highly correlated with the arterial central lab value than the other two. We compare the blood glucose with Accu-check arterial measure and the arterial central lab value to the blood glucose with the Accu-check finger stick and the arterial central lab value.
  • There are several formulas for testing the difference between two dependent correlations. We present the simplest one, developed by Hotelling (1940) and described by Glass and Stanley (1970).

1.2 Other Measures of Correlation

1.2.1 Spearman’s Rho

  • Value of the correlation coefficient is markedly influenced by extreme values and thus does not provide a good description of the relationship between two variables when their distributions are skewed or contain outlying values.
  • Plotting values against a normal distribution to help researchers decide whether a nonparametric procedure should be used.
# === CHEKKING FOR NORMALITY ===
# Review arterial glucose measurement data.
head(glucose_data,5)
# 1. Creating QQ plot with ggpubr library.

# Create a list to store plots.
hist_list=list() 
# Store plots in the list using for loop.
for (column in 1:ncol(glucose_data)) {
  # Creating histograms
  # Histograms will be the 1st, 3rd.. (2n-1) th item in the list. 
  hist_list[[(column*2)-1]] = ggplot(data=NULL,aes(x=glucose_data[,column]))+
    geom_histogram(binwidth = 20,
                   color = "black",
                   fill = "darkgoldenrod3")+
    labs(x="Glucose Measurement (mg/dL)",
         title = colnames(glucose_data)[column])+
    theme_few()
  # Creating qqplots.
  # QQ plots will be the 2nd, 4th.. (2n)th item in the list.
  hist_list[[column*2]] = ggqqplot(data = glucose_data,
                                   x=colnames(glucose_data)[column],
                                   combine = TRUE,
                                   shape = 1,
                                   add = "qqline",
                                   xlab = "Normal Quantiles",
                                   ylab = "Sample Vlues")+
    theme_minimal()
}
# Combine plots with ggarrange function in ggpubr.
ggarrange(plotlist = hist_list,
          labels = NULL,
          font.label = list(size=4),
          ncol = 2,
          nrow = 2)

- A simple method for dealing with the problem of extreme observations in correlation is to rank order the data and then recalculate the correlation on ranks to obtain the nonparametric correlation called Spearman’s rho, or rank. correlation.

  • The Spearman correlation coefficient is defined as Pearson correlation coefficient between the rank variables.
# The correlation between the arterial central lab value and,
# the Accu-chek finge rstick device
# Using Spearman's rho, or rank-correlation.
# H0: The population value of Spearman's rho is = 0.
# H1: The population value of Spearman's rho is not 0.
rstatix::cor_test(data = glucose_data[1:25,],
                  Arterial.Central.Lab,
                  Accu.Fingerstick,
                  alternative = "two.sided",
                  method = "spearman",
                  use = "all.obs") # or "complete.obs"
# Or
cor.test(glucose_data[1:25,"Arterial.Central.Lab"],
         glucose_data[1:25,"Accu.Fingerstick"],method = "spearman")
## 
##  Spearman's rank correlation rho
## 
## data:  glucose_data[1:25, "Arterial.Central.Lab"] and glucose_data[1:25, "Accu.Fingerstick"]
## S = 123.12, p-value = 2.21e-13
## alternative hypothesis: true rho is not equal to 0
## sample estimates:
##       rho 
## 0.9526469
# We reject the null hypothesis and conclude:
# There is sufficient evidence that -->
# A nonparametric correlation exists between the blood glucose measurements
# made by the lab test and the fingerstick device.

# ====Important Note====
# method="spearman" is not a good choice for tied ranks.
# In the case of tied ranks kendall method could be used.

# Another Method
# Convert values to rank 
ranked_glucose_data<-apply(X=-glucose_data[1:25,], 
                          # "-" will ensure highest values to have lowest rank
                          MARGIN = 2,
                          FUN = rank, ties.method="average" )%>%data.frame()

cor.test(ranked_glucose_data$Arterial.Central.Lab,
         ranked_glucose_data$Accu.Fingerstick,
         method="pearson")
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  ranked_glucose_data$Arterial.Central.Lab and ranked_glucose_data$Accu.Fingerstick
## t = 15.025, df = 23, p-value = 2.21e-13
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.8940573 0.9791907
## sample estimates:
##       cor 
## 0.9526469


- To summarize, Spearman’s rho is appropriate when investigators want to measure the relationship between: (1) two ordinal variables, or (2) two numerical variables when one or both are not normally distributed and investigators choose not to use a data transformation (such as taking the logarithm). - Spearman’s rank correlation is especially appropriate when outlying values occur among the observations.

3 Regression

  • The process:
    1. Get sample data
    2. Design a model that works for that sample
    3. Make predictions for the whole population based on the model you have developed.
  • Linear regression: regression measure only a straight-line, or linear, relationship between two variables.
  • Simple regression: that only one explanatory (independent) variable is used to predict an outcome.
  • Multiple regression,more than one independent variable is included in the prediction equation.

3.1 Linear Regression

  • Assumptions in linear regression:
  1. Multivariate Normality : For each value of the X variable, the Y variable is assumed to have a normal distribution.
  2. Homoscedasticity (Equal Variance): No matter the value of the X variable, the standard deviation of Y is assumed to be the same.
  3. Linear relationship between y and each x variables.
  4. Independence of observations. No autocorrelation.
  5. Lack of multicollinearity: Predictors are not correlated with each other.
  6. Outlier check

3.1.1 Least Squares Method

  • There is a dependent variable labeled Y, being predicted. And independent variables labeled X1,X2….XK. These are called predictors. Y is a function of X variables and the regression model is a linear approximation of this function.

  • The easiest regression model is the simple linear regression (population);

\(y= \beta_0 + \beta_1 x_1 + \epsilon\)

  • y: is the variable we are trying to predict and it is called dependent variable.

  • x: independent variable

  • beta1: regression coefficient stands before the independent variable. It quantifies the effect of the x on y.

  • beta0: the constant(intercept)

  • epsilon: error of estimation. The error is the actual difference between the observed and predicted y. At the end everything evens out and on average error is 0.

  • The sample formula which we use in statistics;

\(\hat y= b_0+ b_! x_!\)

  • Note that whenever we have a hat symbol that means it is a estimated or a predicted value.

b0: is the estimate of the regression constant b1: is the estimate of beta1 x: is the sample data for independent variable

  • The Standard Error of the Estimate: The regression equation computed for any one sample of observations is only an estimate of the true population regression equation. If other samples are chosen from the population and a regression equation is calculated for each sample, these equations will vary from one sample to another with respect to both their slopes and their intercepts. An estimate of this variation is standard error of the estimate or standard error of regression. It is based on the squared deviations of the predicted y^’ s from the actual y’s.

3.2 Decomposition of varaiability: SST,SSR,SSE

  • Determinants of good regression
  • There are 3 terms:
  1. Sum of squares total (SST)(TSS): is the squared differences between the observed dependent variable and it’s mean. Much like the variance. It is the measure of total variability of the data set. Also known as total sum of squares, TSS.

Summary of the terms described.

  1. Sum of squares regression (SSR), Sum of Squares Explained : It is the sum of the differences between the predicted value in the mean of the dependent variable. It is a measure that describes how well your line fits the data. If SSR=SST, it means that our regression model captures all the observed variability, and it is perfect. Other notation is ESS, explained sum of squares.

3)Sum of squares error(SSE): smaller is better, also called RSS, residual sum of squares. SSE measures the unexplained variability by the regression.

  • So the mathematical equation is:

\(SS_{explained}=SS_{total}-SS_{residual}\)

  • Total variability of the data set is equal to the variability explained by the regression line plus the unexplained variability known as error. Given a constant total variability, a lower error will cause a better regression. If SSE is closer to zero, explained sum of square move closer to SST. Higher error will cause a less powerful regression.

\(\sum_{i=1}^n (y_i-\overline y)^2 = \sum_{i=1}^n (\hat y_i-\overline y)^2 + \sum_{i=1}^n e_i^2\)

3.3 R-squared

  • There is one widely used measure that describes how powerful a regression is : R squared

\(R^2 = 1- \dfrac{SS_{residual}}{SS_{Total}}\)

  • R squared is equal to variability explained by the regression is divided by the total variability of the data set.

  • R squared is ranging 0-1. But also can be negative. Mostly (.2-.9) R squared=0 means the regression analysis explains none of the variability of the data. R squared=1 means the regression model explains the entire variability of the data.

3.4 Residuals

**

  • A residual is the part of y that is not predicted by X.
  • The correlation between them and the X values should be zero.
  • Stated another way; if the regression model provides a good fit to the data, the values of the residuals are not related to the values of X.
# Extract residuals from regressor object.

3.5 Comparing Two Regression Lines

  • Three statistical questions need to be asked:
  1. Are the slopes equal?
  2. Are the intercepts equal?
  3. Are both the slopes and the intercepts equal?
  • The preferred approach is to use regression models for more than one independent variable-a procedure called multiple regression.

3.6 Adjusted R-squared

  • The formula:
  • n= number of samples/rows in the data set
  • p=

\(R_{adjusted}^2 = 1- \dfrac{(1-R^2)(n-1)}{n-p-1}\)

\(n=\text{number of samples/rows in the dataset}\)

\(p=\text{number of predictors/features}\)

4 Statistical Methods for Multiple Variables

4.1 Multiple Regression

  • The formula:

\(y=a+b_1X_1+b_2X_2+......b_nX_n\)

  • This arithmetic equation is called a linear combination; thus, the response variable Y can be expressed as a (linear) combination of the explanatory variables.
  • In multiple regression analysis results may not be replicable if the independent variables are highly correlated with each other.
  • Ridge regression is a technique for analyzing multiple regression data that suffer from multi collinearity by reducing the size of standard errors.
  • In multiple regression, a given regression coefficient indicates how much the predicted value of y changes each time X increases by 1 unit, holding the values of all other variables in the regression equation constant though all subjects had the same value on the other variables.
  • This feature of multiple regression makes it an ideal method to control for baseline differences and confounding variables.

# After BMI, age and race are entered into the regression equation,
# 0.93 indicates that more than 63% of the variability in %fat is -->
# accounted for by knowing patients BMI, age, and race. 
# Because it is less than 1 -->
# we know that factors other than those included in the study also
# play a role in determining a person's percent body fut.

4.2 Standardized Regression Coefficients

  • Sizes of the unstandardized regression coefficients cannot be used to decide which independent variables are the most important, because their size is also related to the scale on which the variables are measured.
  • One way to eliminate the effect of scale is to standardize the regression coefficients. Standardization can be done by subtracting the mean value of X and dividing by the standard deviation before analysis, so that all variables have a mean of 0 and a standard deviation of 1.
  • It is also possible to calculate the standardized regression coefficients after the regression model has been developed. The larger the standardized coefficient, the larger the value of the t statistic. Standardized regression coefficients are often referred to as beta (ß) coefficients.

4.3 Multiple R

  • Multiple R squared is reported in summary(lm).
  • Multiple R is the multiple-regression analogue of the Pearson product moment correlation coefficient r.
  • The correlation between predicted percent value and the actual value.
  • If the multiple R is squared, it measures how much of the variation in the actual depression score is accounted for by knowing the information included in the regression equation.

4.4 Selecting Variables for Regression Models

  • Deciding on the variables that provide the best prediction is a process sometimes referred to as model building.

  • Forward selection: Begins with one variable in the regression equation; then, additional variables are added one at a time until all statistically significant variables are included in the equation. The first variable in the regression equation is the X variable that has the highest correlation with the response variable y. The next X variable considered for the regression equation is the one that increases R-squared by the largest amount. If the increment in R-squared is statistically significant by the F test, it is included in the regression equation. This step-by-step procedure continues until no X variables remain that produce a significant increase in R-squared.

  • Backward elimination: All variables are initially included in the regression equation. The X variable that would reduce R-squared by the smallest increment is removed from the equation. If the resulting decrease is not statistically significant, that variable is permanently removed from the equation.

  • When features of both the forward selection and the backward elimination procedures are used together, the method is called stepwise regression (stepwise selection).

  • Variables are sometimes grouped according to their function, such as all demographic characteristics, and added to the regression equation as a group or block; this process is often called hierarchical regression.

4.5 Polynomial Regression

  • The formula:

\(y=b_0+b_1X+b_2X^2+....b_nX^n\)

  • Example:

4.6 Cross Validation

  • If the equation is to be used to predict outcomes for future subject, it should, therefore, be validated on a second sample, a process called cross validation.
  • The regression equation is used to predict the outcome in the second sample, and the predicted outcomes are compared with the actual outcomes; the correlation between the predicted and actual values indicates how well the model fits.
  • Researchers can hold out a proportion of the subjects for cross validation, perhaps 20% or 25%. The holdout sample should be randomly selected from the entire sample prior to the original analysis. The predicted outcomes in the holdout sample are compared with the actual outcomes, often using R-squared to judge how well the findings cross-validate.
  • Another method is the jackknife in which one observation is left out of the sample, call it x1; regression is performed using the n - 1 observations, and the results are applied to x1. Then this observation is returned to the sample, and another, x2 is held out. This process continues until there is a predicted outcome for each observation in the sample; the predicted and actual outcomes are then compared.
  • The bootstrap method works in a similar manner, although the goal is different. The bootstrap can be used with small samples to estimate the standard error and confidence intervals.

5 Controlling For Cofounding

5.1 Analysis of Covariance

  • For further reading please refer to: https://www.r-bloggers.com/2021/10/analysis-of-covariance-ancova-using-r/

  • Analysis of covariance (ANCOVA) is the statistical technique used to control for the influence of a confounding variable. Confounding variables occur most often when subjects cannot be assigned at random to different groups, that is, when the groups of interest already exist.

  • ANCOVA is a general linear model which blends ANOVA and regression. ANCOVA requires at least one continuous and one categorical independent variable known as treatment. Covariate is an additional continuous independent variable in ANCOVA (also known as co-founding variable, contaminant). By statistically modifying the influence of covariate, ANCOVA evaluates differences between groups in a categorical independent variable. ANCOV basically removes the variance associated with covariate.

  • Mathematically, ANCOVA decomposes the variance in the dependent variable into variance explained by the covariates, variance explained by the categorical independent variables, and residual variance.

  • In ANCOVA, the adjusted Y mean for a given group (j) is obtained by:

\(Adjusted\ \overline{y_j}=Unadjusted\ \overline{y_j}+b(\overline{X_j}-\overline{X})\)

\(\overline{X}= \text{global mean of covariate}\)

  • Useful methods to control for confounding variables are analysis of covariance (ANCOVA) and the Mantel-Haenszel chi-square procedure. It is appropriate to use ANCOVA when the dependent variable is numerical and the independent measures are grouping variables on a nominal scale (e.g., smoking vs. nonsmoking), and confounding variables occur.

  • If the dependent measure is also nominal, such as whether a patient has survived to a given time, the Mantd-Haenszel chi-square can be used to control for the effect of a confounding variable.

  • Linear model formula for ANCOVA:

\(y=b_0+b_1X+b_2Z+b_3XZ\)

  • The regression lines have equal slopes and are parallel when b3 is 0, that is, no interaction between the independent variable X and Z.

  • The regression lines have equal intercepts and equal slopes (are coincident) if both b2 and b3 are O.

  • Assumptions of ANCOVA

  1. Independence of observations.
  2. Normality and homogeneity of variances.
  3. Linearity assumption: At each level of categorical independent variable, the covariate should be linearly related to the dependent variable. If the relationship is no linear, the adjustment made to covariate will be biased.
  4. Homogeneity of within-groups regression slopes (parallelism or non interaction). There should be no interaction between categorical independent variable and covariate. The regression lines between the covariate and dependent variable for each group of independent variable should be parallel. (same slope)
  5. Dependent variable and covariate should be measured in continuous scale.
  6. Covariate should be measured without error or little error as possible.
# ANCOVA Example
# Question: Is there a difference in %Body-Fat of Man and Woman.
# BMI is a co-founding factor in this example.

6 Predicting Nominal Outcomes

6.1 Logistic Regression

  • Many outcomes in health are nominal, actually binary, variables-they either occur or do not occur.
  • Regression coefficients obtained in logistic regression can be transformed into odds ratios.
  • Logistic regression provides a way to obtain an odds ratio for a given risk factor that controls for, or is adjusted for, confounding variables; in other words, we can do analysis of covariance with logistic regression as well as with multiple linear regression.
  • Logistic regression is commonly used when the independent variables include both numerical and nominal measures and the outcome variable is binary.
  • The logistic model gives the probability that the outcome, occurs as an exponential function of the independent variables.
  • The model is:

\(P_X=\dfrac{1}{1+exp[-(b_0+b_1X_1+b_2X_2+b_3X_3)]}\)

\(exp=\text{the base of the natural logarithm (2.718) is taken to the power shown in parentheses}\)

  • In logistic regression model response variable is log odds:

\(ln(odds)=ln(\dfrac{p}{1-p})=b_0+b_1X_1+b_2X_2\)

  • Regression coefficient can be interpreted in terms of relative risks in cohort studies or odds ratios in case-control studies.

  • One advantage of logistic regression is that it requires no assumptions about the distribution of the independent variables.

  • A chisquare test (instead of the tor F test) is used to determine whether a variable adds significantly to the prediction.

  • The logistic equation can be used to find the probability for any given individual.

  • The overall results from a logistic regression may be tested with Hosmer and Lemeshow’s goodness of fit test. The test is based on the chi-square distribution. A p value ,0.05 means that the model’s estimates fit the data at an acceptable level.

  • Logistic Regression Example:

  • Data set Explanation: use of logistic regression to identify patients that may experience an extended length of stay in the hospital (> 7 days) based on clinical indications. Shah and his co investigators (2018) wanted to develop a model to help hospital staff predict which patients with pulmonary hypertension may experience long postoperative stays in the hospital.

6.2 Log Linear Analysis

  • Log linear analysis can be used when each independent variable in a research problem is measured on a categorical or nominal scale (age, onset, and familial status), as is the outcome variable (occurrence of symptom etc.).

  • If only two variables are being analyzed, the chi-square method introduced can be used to determine whether a relationship exists between them; with three or more nominal or categorical variables, a statistical method called log-linear analysis is appropriate. Log-linear analysis is analogous to a regression model in which all the variables, both independent and dependent, are measured on a nominal scale. The technique is called log-linear because it involves using the logarithm of the observed frequencies in the contingency table.

  • Log linear models model cell counts in contingency tables. Log linear models do not distinguish between response and explanatory variables. All variables in log linear model are essentially “response”. That’s why log linear analysis may also be used to analyze multidimensional contingency tables in situations in which no distinction exists between independent and dependent variables, that is, when investigators simply want to examine the relationship among a set of nominal measures.

  • For a contingency table: Cell count in a row i and column j is equal to the product of the marginal probabilities and the number of observations. This can be expressed as:

\(\mu_{ij}=n\pi_i\pi_j\)

  • If we take the log of each side it becomes additive (linear). Below equation displays log linear model of independence for two-way contingency table.

\(log\mu_{ij}=logn+log\pi_i+log\pi_j\)

  • If these two variables are not independent, this model does not work well. In that case additional parameter for interaction could be added to the model.
  • Below example researchers are interested in how cell counts in contingency table depend on the levels of the categorical variable. Important Note: If researchers were interested in modeling a categorical variable (marijuana use in the below example) as a function of other two variables, then they would use logistic regression. But they were interested in understanding the relationship between all three variables without one necessarily being the response variable (Log linear model).

6.3 Deviance, AIC and Saturated Models

  1. Null Model: It has only one parameter, which is intercept aka mean of all the data points. For bivariate model, this is a horizontal line with the same prediction for every point.
  2. Saturated Model: Where the number of parameters/coefficients is equal to the number of data points. The line of curve passes through every point. It takes into account all the variance in the data. Over fitted model. Saturated model has a high variance.
  3. Proposed Model: is considered best fit and has number of parameters in-between the null and saturated models.

  • Deviance is a measure of goodness of fit of generalized linear model. Rather is is a measure o badness of fit- higher numbers indicate worse fit. It is defined as the difference between the saturated and proposed models. In other words deviance is a measure of error. The greater the deviance, the worse the model fits compared to the best case (saturated model). R reports two forms of deviance- the null deviance and the residual deviance.

  • The null deviance shows how well the response variable is predicted by a model that includes only the intercept (grand mean). It is the log likelihood difference between null model and saturated model with df= dfSaturated-dfNull.

  • Residual deviance is the log likelihood difference between proposed and saturated models. Including meaningful independent variables are expected to reduce residual deviance significant amount.

  • Acaine Information Criterion provides a method for assessing model quality through comparison of related models. In the context of having more than one similar candidate models, the model with the smallest AIC value should be selected. It is not interpretable on its own.

6.3.1 [Chi-Square Goodness of Fit]{style=“color:red;

  • The formula is simple,

  • O : Observed value, E : Expected value

\(X^2 = \sum {\dfrac {(O-E)^2}{E}}\)

  • Basically what er are doing is: comparing observed values to expected values. Comparing sampling distribution to expected probability distribution.

  • The steps to calculate chi-square is the same as the other tests. State the hypothesis. Set significance level. Determine the critical value. Compute the chi-square. Make decisions. Draw conclusions.

# Number of students eats at a specific cafe on each day are listed as a data frame. 

cafe <- data.frame(Monday=68, Tuesday=80, Wednesday=64, Thursday=56, Friday=52)
cafe
# The cafe owner wants to know if the same number of students eat at the cafe every day. 

# Step 1 : Hypothesis, H0: The proportions are equal (.2), H1: At least one of the proportions are not equal (.2)

# Step 2 : Set significance, Alpha = .05
# Step 3 : Find the critical region, degrees of freedom = c-1=5-1=4 chi-square 9.49

# If we use the formula presented we will get the number chi-square 7.75 which is less than the critical value 9.49. Therefore we do not reject the null hypothesis. 

# Using the function chisq.test: x=data we want to compare, p= expected proportion for each observation. In our case it is .2 for each element in our vector. 

chisq.test(x=cafe[1,], p=rep(.2, times=length(cafe[1,])))
## 
##  Chi-squared test for given probabilities
## 
## data:  cafe[1, ]
## X-squared = 7.5, df = 4, p-value = 0.1117
# p value is greate than .05 which means there is no statistically significant difference between number of students eats in the cafe each day.
